'''Staines-upon-Thames''' is a town on the [[bank (geography)|left bank]] of the [[River Thames]] in [[Surrey]], England, in the [[borough of Spelthorne]]. At or near the Roman settlement of '''Pontibus''', it became '''Stanes''' and then '''Staines'''. Its borough is in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Middlesex]] and its two [[Urban districts of Great Britain and Ireland|precursor districts]] were transferred to Surrey County Council in 1965.

The town is inside the [[M25 motorway]], {{convert|17|miles|km}} south-west of [[Charing Cross]]. It is within the [[London Commuter Belt]] and the [[Greater London Urban Area]], and adjoins part of the [[Metropolitan Green Belt|Green Belt]]. Passing along the edge of the town and crossing [[Staines Bridge]] is the [[Thames Path National Trail]]. The bridge is one of many re-buildings. It was built from 1827&amp;ndash;1832, to white granite-faced designs by [[George Rennie (engineer)|George Rennie]]. 
